{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"039b010b-4525-475a-89ed-dee675ecf154","content":"**MSTest.Sdk 4.x dropped the VSTest compatibility layer by default.**\n\nStarting with MSTest.Sdk 4.0, the SDK uses **Microsoft.Testing.Platform** as the sole test runner and no longer emits the VSTest bridge/adapter assemblies. This means `vstest.console` (and `dotnet test` in its legacy VSTest mode) can't discover or run your tests.\n\n**Your options:**\n\n1. **Re-enable VSTest support** — add this to your `.csproj`:\n   ```xml\n   <EnableMicrosoftTestingExtensionsCodeCoverage>true</EnableMicrosoftTestingExtensionsCodeCoverage>\n   ```\n   or more directly:\n   ```xml\n   <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n   <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n   ```\n\n2. **Switch your CI to use `dotnet test` with the new platform** — MSTest.Sdk 4.x projects produce a self-contained test executable. Run tests with:\n   ```bash\n   dotnet test          # works if TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport is true (default in 4.x)\n   dotnet run --project TestProject.csproj\n   ```\n\n3. **Or invoke the test binary directly:**\n   ```bash\n   ./TestProject --report-trx\n   ```\n\nThe recommended migration path is option **2** — retire `vstest.console` from your pipeline and rely on `dotnet test` (which now delegates to Microsoft.Testing.Platform under the hood in SDK 4.x).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3ced8af3-171b-448b-9b75-f66caf8c0807","outputTokens":390,"requestId":"E3C1:349DAE:C452C8:DFB406:6A053F7E"},"id":"7036e4b4-aca8-4123-83b4-30eb52d7287a","timestamp":"2026-05-14T03:20:40.670Z","parentId":"1ae021b7-f699-4b9c-b956-6885f1a79e39"}
